<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0129 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1249EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-HowardBeach     05-24 0179</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Howard Beach,0181</SECOND><HEAD>One of Seven Remaining Defendants Pleads Guilty</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of the seven remaining defendants in theHoward Beach case pleaded guilty to felony riot charges todaybefore jury selection resumed in the second trial stemming from thealleged racial attack.   Salvatore DeSimone, 20, also pleaded guilty to a misdemeanorcharge of criminal facilitation for driving members of a white gangon Dec. 20, 1986. DeSimone entered his plea before state SupremeCourt Justice Thomas Demakos, who released transcripts todayinvolving the guilty plea of another defendant.   DeSimone's attorney, Augustus Agate, said that as part of theplea, his client will not be required to testify against the otherdefendants in the case. He also said DeSimone would receiveyouthful offender status and avoid a jail term at his June 27sentencing.   During his plea, DeSimone contradicted statements attributed tohim in a police report about the incident, which left 23-year-oldMichael Griffith dead after he was struck and killed by a car on anearby highway.   DeSimone left the courthouse without comment.</TEXT></DOC>